  "prompt": "What is the square root of 40 in radical form?",
  "response": "The square root of 40 in radical form is expressed as \\(\\sqrt{40}\\). This can be further simplified. You can break down 40 into its prime factors: \n\n\\[ 40 = 2^3 \\times 5 \\]\n\nYou can then pair the factors in groups of two for simplification, giving:\n\n\\[ \\sqrt{40} = \\sqrt{2^3 \\times 5} = \\sqrt{2^2 \\times 2 \\times 5} = \\sqrt{4 \\times 10} \\]\n\nSince the square root of 4 is 2, you can simplify this to:\n\n\\[ \\sqrt{40} = 2\\sqrt{10} \\]\n\nSo, the simplified radical form of \\(\\sqrt{40}\\) is \\(2\\sqrt{10}\\).",
